\begin_layout Section
Summary 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model aims to explain how consumer behaviour with respect to effort
 or investment towards their own status changes in response to income difference
s 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\equiv y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are disposable incomes for the poor and rich consumers (respectively).
 A fundamental assumption for the model is that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are fixed in the short-term horizon considered by the consumer.
 The resetting of wealth at a certain period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

 is also an intrinsic feature of the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We proceed by first discussing the degenerate case when players (consumers)
 maximise accumulated assets at an infinite horizon.
 After discussing the futility of positional competition in such a game,
 we consider myopic consumers who are concerned with the next immediate
 single-period (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The Nash Equilibrium solution for this problem and its implications for
 effects of income differences are discussed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The notion of rich and poor is normative in the model and allows a discussion
 of how the parameters controlling promotion and demotion must satisfy a
 population constraint - which is the argument that neither promotions nor
 demotions can continue forever in a closed economy.
 This is further detailed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main changes that have been made since the previous version of the model
 are as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Time Horizons} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - While the previous model fixed the time-horizons when the assets were
 reset in the positional game, the current model adopts a more general approach
 to time-horizons - allowing assets to reset at a general interval 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\tau$
\end_inset

 rather than at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2$
\end_inset

.
 While the solution in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 still deals with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=2$
\end_inset

, a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 amounts to a higher consumer myopia (i.e.
 shorter time-horizon) for positional game in the model.
 The assumptions pertaining to the short-term horizon are detailed in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Asset resets as no bequest} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - Unlike the previous model which assumed presence of calamitous risk to
 accumulated assets, the current model interprets the long-term horizon
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 as the end-of-life for the consumer.
 The reset only represents the fact that the consumer is unable to transfer
 her accumulated assets to the progeny.
 In this no-bequest model, the consumer banks upon entirely on the game
 of social positions at the end of her life-cycle.
 The feature thus accommodates the dissimilarity between social and economic
 positions as well - as it is possible for a significant number of players
 (consumers) ti achieve a higher socio-economic position in life while still
 failing to transfer their social status to progeny after end-of-life (see
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Maximisation of Assets accumulation at the start of next period} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - Instead of assuming a particular shape of utility function, a closed-form
 solution is discussed with consumers maximise expected assets under risk-neutra
l preferences.
 The martingale requirement for expected asset maximisation is discussed
 and the relevant assumptions are made for optimisation of total assets
 over the short-term horizon (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The effort or investment in the next period is ignored in the short-term
 horizon which the consumer maximises expected assets over.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Concave Promotion and demotion functions} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - The promotion and demotion functions are assumed to have a concave (rather
 than logistic) form in the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Long-term population constraint} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - The population constraint - which is a normative concern in the model
 - is imposed only in the long-term in the model and has no role for the
 consumer in the short-term asset maximisation.
 This amounts to a constraint on the ratio of promotions to demotions in
 the long-term i.e.
 that on the parameters controlling 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the promotion of demotion functions for poor and rich consumers (respectively).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"

\end_inset

Single-Period Assets Maximisation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now discuss the Nash Equilibrium solution under population constraint
 for the maximisation of assets in a single period.
 The time-horizon relevant for maximisation of assets extends only to the
 immediate next period that the consumer considers to exercise her selection
 of investment or effort 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 in the current period.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to see that the consumer time-horizon must be finite in the positiona
l game - which would be inconsequential if the poor and rich consumers already
 were aware of their infinite-horizon assets.
 If there exist long-term evaluations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

 of the future assets for poor and rich consumers (respectively), then the
 net addition to the assets through the positional game would be zero in
 the long-term equilibrium.
 In this equilibrium, the poor and rich consumers would choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 (respectively) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}-\nu_{1,t}+\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})\mathscr{A}_{2}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))\mathscr{A}_{1}}{\delta}=\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}-\nu_{2,t}+\frac{L(\nu_{2,t})\mathscr{A}_{1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))\mathscr{A}_{2}}{\delta}=\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

- where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are incomes for poorer consumer 1 and richer consumer 2 (respectively),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 represents the time-value of money i.e.
 a discount factor and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})$
\end_inset

 are functions for promotion and demotion functions for two respective positions
 (poor and rich) in the game.
 One way this can be achieved is be having 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}=\nu_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}=\nu_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 when consumer spends all of their income in the effort (investment) and
 their economic position remains stable (due to promotion and demotion probabili
ties implied by 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})$
\end_inset

 respectively).
 Any other possible solutions must also maintain that no net value is added
 to the long-term values 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and thus positional game is inconsequential for either of the consumers.
 Such a result does not seem at odds for what we observe about status competitio
ns.
 Not only does economic history offer enough instances of perceivedly permanent
 (infinite) economic differences leading to unrest, the maximisation of
 terminal assets leads to well-known paradoxes in consumer behaviour (see
 St.
 Petersburg paradox
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While a multiple-period maximisation is possible, we avoid it for two reasons.
 First, the single-period solution is sufficient for income-gap effects
 that we wish to explain with the model and avoids the need to ascertain
 martingale conditions in the multiple period solution (using a transform
 to the risk-neutral probability measure that ensures additivity of assets
 accumulated over multiple time periods - as explained by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "harrison1981martingales"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Second, the assumption of single-period maximisation allows for more general
 utility functions (e.g.
 with risk-aversion) to be considered as the risk-neutrality condition can
 be relieved when consumers maximise their utility from assets in a single-perio
d.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the assumption of consumer myopia, we turn our attention on maximisation
 of assets for until the immediately next period.
 The single-period horizon for the consumer implies that the assets maximised
 by the consumer in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 do not include the effort or investment in the next period i.e.
 the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 should not include 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t+1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2,t+1}$
\end_inset

).
 This allows us to solve for consumer 1's strategy i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t\in[1,\tau]}$
\end_inset

 by iterations starting with period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 and finishing at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

.
 This poorer consumer in a period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 would thus need to maximise the following function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
y_{1,t}-\nu_{1,t}+\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer1genoptimfunc}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 are the incomes in a period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 is the effort in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 is the promotion probability in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that at the end-of-life i.e.
 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

, the consumer (a risk-neutral dynast) cannot carry over the accumulated
 assets and must spend everything on the position game - thus letting the
 assets to be augmented in the last period by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{W(y_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(y_{2,t1}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer1genlastperiod}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the consumer 2 i.e.
 the richer consumer maximises the following function in every period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
y_{2,t}-\nu_{2,t}+\frac{L(\nu_{2,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))y_{1,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer2genoptimfunc}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer 2 i.e.
 the richer consumer would add the following value to her assets in the
 last period
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{W(y_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(y_{2,t1}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer2genlastperiod}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"

\end_inset

Nash Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To discuss the solution of the equilibrium, we impose two specific conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Long-term Incomes}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - The income in every period to the consumers remains the same so that
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 With same income assumed in every period and with the maximisation of assets
 (rather than a utility that may consider satiation with assets), the asset
 increments at every period except the last period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

 are the same.
 More specifically, the consumer behaviour in every period 
\begin_inset Formula $t\ne\tau$
\end_inset

 is one where the poorer (or richer) consumer adds 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})y_{2}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))y_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})y_{1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))y_{2}$
\end_inset

) in any time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t\ne\tau$
\end_inset

 - while in the last period, the consumer sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,\tau}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2,\tau}=y_{2}$
\end_inset

 ) hoping to have 
\begin_inset Formula $W(y_{1})y_{2}+(1-W(y_{1}))y_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $L(y_{2})y_{1}+(1-L(y_{2}))y_{2}$
\end_inset

 ) in the first period (without considering the effort or investment 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,1},\nu_{2,1}$
\end_inset

 in the first period after the reset).
 The solution in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 therefore only considers two periods i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Concave promotion and demotion functions}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - A specific set of (concave) promotion and demotion functions are chosen
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1})=1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{a\nu_{1}+1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2})=\frac{1}{\sqrt{a\nu_{2}+1}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The functions for promotion and demotion of the poor and rich consumers
 (respectively) must satisfy both of the following conditions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
increasing (decreasing) in 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 increases while 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 decreases with higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

) and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
asymptotic to unity (zero) so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\nu\rightarrow\infty}W(\nu)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\nu\rightarrow\infty}L(\nu)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the promotion and demotions functions (
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 respectively) do not represent distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 - but are binary distributions with a mean modified by 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (see Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The expectation of promotions is therefore defined for a particular 
