\begin_layout Standard
So far we have treated the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as exogenous in the model.
 A necessary constraint on the parameters follows from the observation that
 for social positions to be maintained - the promotions and demotions must
 balance each other in the long-term.
 The observation banks upon the constraints on social growth that have been
 been discussed in the economic literature at least since 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HarrodGrowth1958"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (also see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "scitovskyjoyless1992,HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ).
 In the above model, the life-standards that determine the rich or poor
 status of the consumer - categories which exist so long as there is one
 poor or one rich person in the long-term - are assumed to be exogenous
 and to evolve with the income differences 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 The balance of demotions and promotions is also subject to the proportions
 of poor and rich in the population and influences the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 through the life-standards in the economy (see discussion in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ProportionsRichPoor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a life-cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and the single-periods within them (each which are represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[1,\tau]$
\end_inset

 that the consumers maximise assets over), the long-term stability of promotions
 and demotions means that the net demotions over a few life-cycles would
 balance out the promotions.
 To consider what the constraint means in terms of the above model, we define
 the ratio of promotions to demotions in every period as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\rho(t) & =\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})}{L(\nu_{2,t})}\label{eq:rho_ratio}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An implicit assumption with the above definition (Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rho_ratio"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is that at any point in time, there are a certain number of consumers
 in a given period of their life-cycle (time horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 (as respective probabilities of promotion and demotion).
 In other words, the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t)$
\end_inset

 represents a comparison between two consumers with synchronised long-term
 and short-term horizons (the issue is simplified when we consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=2$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore, using the forms of 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 defined in Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W(\nu_{1}^{*}) & =1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{a\nu_{1}^{*}+1}}=1-(\frac{2\delta}{y_{2}-y_{1}})^{1/3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L(\nu_{2}^{*}) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{b\nu_{2}^{*}+1}}=(\frac{2\delta}{y_{2}-y_{1}})^{1/3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\rho(t) & =(\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{2\delta})^{1/3}-1\label{eq:rho_t_solution}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ratio of promotions vs demotions thus depends only on income differences
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the discount factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 As we have argued before, higher income differences 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 must increase promotions in the equilibrium.
 However, promotions in the long-term must also be balanced by demotions
 because of population stability so that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}{\rho(t)} & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the forms of 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 defined in Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, there are two possibilities for the constraint to be met.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The high income differences are balanced by periods of low income differences
 letting the term 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{2\delta})^{1/3}$
\end_inset

 fluctuate above and below 1 in the long-term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The discount factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 - which represents the time value of money in the above formulation (i.e.
 a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 implying a higher normative impatience of the consumers) would rise to
 lower the term 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{2\delta})^{1/3}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the impatience for investment (or consumption) in the current
 period (rather than the next) may rise to satisfy the population constraint.
\end_layout

