\begin_layout Standard
[SUDDEN RISE in PROMOTIONS]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sudden rise in promotions is possible and it means moving to a different
 equilibrium where demotions would balance the promotions in the long term.
 Sudden promotions - which mean more consumers with higher income - indicate
 rise in in the proportion of rich and poor in absolute terms.
 In the economy with more money, when there are too many rich and the income
 differences are maintained as the same, then more rich (past promotions)
 raise the separating line in absolute terms (through consumption or saving).
 Demotions therefore rise simply because many of those who were rich would
 end up becoming poor again both due to more money in the market and the
 raise standards of richness.
 The population constraint we have discussed so far is thus constituted
 in the possibility of the rise in overall income.
 Notice that the population constraint need not impose anything on 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 in the short-term when 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 are fixed for the consumer.
 The changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 over the long-term are what must satisfy the population constraint.
 
\end_layout

